{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393347387/1938032101/0315.xml":{"full_text":"European Powers\nMove Towards Peace\n(Continued from Page 1)\nelan wars and nowhere in Europe\nIs there a government that wants\nwar now.\nEngland does not want It until her\nrearmament program, particularly\nthe expansion of her air force, is\ncompleted.\nFrance, seeking to stabilize an un\ncertain internal situation, does not\nwant it.\nSoviet Russia, busy consolidating\nthe Stalin regime through liquida\ntion of many old-time Bolshevists,\ndoes not want it.\nNot Seeking Territory\nNone of those three great powers\nseeks territory. What they do seek,\nand seek desperately, is preservation\nof the status quo. To keep peace,\nEngland, France and Russia are\nWilling to endure almost any provo\ncation except direct attack. For ex\nample, the best information is that\nSoviet Russia would not have re\nsorted to military intervention if\nPoland had invaded Lithuania. It\nis uncertain whether France would\nattack Germany if Adolf Hitler\nshould attempt to absorb 3,500,000\nGermans in Czechoslovakia.\nBut informed persons believe Hit\nler probably will refrain from fur\nther Balkan adventures until he\nQthuaniaupset\u201d\nBY RESIGNATIONS\n(Continued from Page 1)\nread here with wry smiles. But\noutwardly the country was quiet.\nThere were no manifestations or\ndemonstrations. But political lead\ners were crestfallen and silent. Mast\nof the people generally seemed re\nlieved that at least the danger of\nwar with an overwhelmingly more\npowerful neighbor had been averted.\nPoland Masses Troops\nWarsaw, March 21.\u2014(UP)\u2014Po\nland Intends to maintain an army\nmassed on the Lithuanian fron\ntier until diplomatic relations have\nbeen established in keeping with\nIts ultimatum, it was understood to\n^Three divisions, totalling 50,000\nmen, paraded yesterday at Vilna, 10\nmiles from the frontier, and simi\nlar demonstrations were planned.\nOfficially, they are \u201cnormal army\nmaneuvers\u201d but it is understood\ntheir end will coincide with the\nestablishment of legations at War\nsaw and Kaunas. A similar situa\ntion is planned as regards the fleet\nconcentrated off Lithuanias coas..\nCavalry and tanks were promin\nent in yesterday's parade\u2014a sign\nOf the mobility of the frontier army\n_and 50 airplanes circled over the\nSatisfied at Result\nOfficials asserted that they were\nmost satisfied with the outcome of\ntheir sudden demand on Lithuania,\nand as regards angry public dem\nonstrations termed them \u201cisolated\nInstances.\u201d\nIn such demonstrations here yes\nterday, 435 persons were arrested\nas thousands tried to inarch to the\nforeign office to protest against\nthe Lithuanian settlement. The\ncrowd clamored for annexation of\nLithuania.\nPolice dispersed the demonstra\ntors only after firemen played hoses\ninto the crowd for 20 minutes. Most\nof the persons arrested were\ndrenched.\nMany students were in the dem\nonstration, organized by the ex\ntreme Nationalistic group. Orators\ndemanded an immediate march on\nKaunas. Then, the original 3,000\ndemonstrators started toward the\nforeign office. Thousands more\nJoined them. Police first summoned\nriot squads in motor trucks, then\nthe firemen.\nCol. Josef Beck, foreign minister,\nis to address the senate Wednesday\non the Lithuanian situation, and it\nwas predicted he might suggest\nthe formation of a Baltic block of\nnations including Poland, Lithuania,\nEsthonia, Finland and Latvia. In\nsuch a block. Lithuania would be\nexpected to end her understanding\nwith Russia.\nBeck may also refer to several\npoints which remain outstanding\nwith Lithuania, which Poland wants\nto settle by diplomatic negotiations.\nForeign observers here foresaw the\npossibility that Lithuania might be\nreluctant to settle on Polish terms.\nMOHICAN\nTUESDAY\nSPECIALS\n14 to 20 North Main St.\nFRESH FROM TIIE HEARTH\nCORN TOP\nBREAD\nFull MgV\nPound\n\"Homey\u201d i7\nTypo r\nLoaf\nJELLY FILLED\nDONUTS doz 17c\nRegular Price 25c Dozen\nA REAL BARGAIN MEAL\nCORNED BEEF\nDINNER\n3 lbs Plate Corned Beef\n1 head Cabbage\u2014I Turnip\n2 lbs Potatoes 1 lb Carrots\n1 Shopping Bag\nThe\nWhole\nBag-Full\nFor\n35^\nCLEAN NEW\nWALNUT\nMEATS ft\n39\n1U\nW1CKFORD\nCLAMS qt.\nFor Steaming or Chowder\n&IEADOWBROOK MILK\u2014\nRICH CREAMY MUNSTER\nTASTY YOUNG AMERICAN\nCHEESE\nlb 19/\nSpecial\nOne\nDay\nPrice\nconsolidates his position In Austria.\nThe bite that Germany took out of\nmiddle Europe when she absorbed\nAustria seems to have appeased the\nNazi hunger for land temporarily.\nNow she must digest what she has\neaten. Hitler now controls the bot\ntle neck through which land, air\nand water communications to south\neastern Europe must flow. Thus he\nis in a position to fulfill one of his\nambitions\u2014the break-up of the lit\ntle entente\u2014by economic and diplo\nmatic pressure rather than a resort\nto arms.\nAttitude of Restraint\nHitler\u2019s speech of Friday reflected\nthis new attitude of restraint. He\ndevoted most of it to a justification\nof his Austrian putsch. It was de\nvoid of threats. He omitted his cus\ntomary denunciation of Bolshevism\nand avoided special mention of\nCzechoslovakia. The Interpretation\nplaced on that speech here is that\nhe does not desire to provoke Soviet\nRussia and that he has decided to\nstep warily in view of the fact that\nFrance has reaffirmed her Intention\nof defending Czechoslovakia against\naggression.\nBut it would be dangerous to be\ntoo optimistic over a contention\nwhich so many nations are clustered,\nseparated, in many cases, by nothing\nbut artificial boundaries. Resump\ntion of diplomatic relations between\nPoland and Lithuania will not mean\nthat all their problems have been\nsolved. Poland still wants auton\nomy for the 200.000 Poles in Lithu\nania; she wants access to Lithu\nania\u2019s Baltic ports; she wants to\ndrive a diplomatic wedge between\nLithuania and Soviet Russia.\nSituation Less Critical\nThe situation in Czechoslovakia is\nless critical. The apparent willing\nness of the Czechs to give German\nborn citizens a more authoritative\nvoice in the government has eased\ntension.\nA hopeful note for the peace of\nEurope even has come out of war\ntorn Spain. The statement of Rebel\nGeneralissimo Francisco Franco that\nhe will do nothing to change the\nstatus quo in the western Mediter\nranean in event of victory, and will\nnot cede an inch of territory to any\nforeign power was regarded as re\nassuring for the future.\nMeantime, Franco is giving Europe\na preview of the horrors of the next\nwar by his merciless bombing of\nBarcelona.\nTwo Americans have made power\nful contributions to peace in the last\nfew days. One was former President\nHerbert Hoover who said, after vis\niting 15 nations and interviewing\nleading statesmen, that war is un\nlikely in the near future. He be\nlieves that, in general, the will to\npeace is much stronger now than\nthe will to war and he pointed out\nthat the principal nations would not\nbe prepared for war for two or three\nyears.\nKennedy Speech Impressive\nThere was impressive reaction\nthroughout Europe to the speech of\nJoseph Kennedy, new American am\nbassador to England, who advised\nevery one against proceeding on the\ndangerous assumption that the\nUnited States would not fight under\nany circumstances short of actual\ninvasion. Europe has not forgotten\nthat American men and money de\nlivered the knockout blow in the\nWorld war.\nFrench and British political lead\ners are increasing their attempts to\nappease the \u201chungry\" nations. Typi\ncal of this were the strong diplo\nmatic appeals of France and Britain\nto Poland and Lithuania to recon\ncile their differences. And always\nin the background is the implied\nthreat of an ever-increasing British\nnavy and a strong French army.\nThe tragedy of Europe today, and\nthe gravest threat to its peace, is\nthe fact that the observance of\ntreaties has broken down. All na\ntions have reverted to \u201cpower poli\ntics\u201d in which nothing matters ex\ncept force. When and if war comes,\nthe failure of nations to live up to\ntheir pledged word will have been\na contributing factor.\nGOOD ADVICE TO\nTAKE THESE DAYS\nBoston, March 21 (UP) Ten\n\u201cdepression antidotes\u201d were pre\nscribed today at Boston University.\nTo win success in the face of\nhard times, Dean Everett W. Lord\nof the college of business adminis\ntration advised this year's graduat\ning class to: \u201c1\u2014Be yourself. Ana\nlyze your personality; cultivate the\ndesirable\u2014repress the undesirable.\n2\u2014Be alert. Look for opportunities\nto express yourself; 3\u2014Be positive.\nDetermine your goal and the route\nto it; 4\u2014Be systematic. Take one\nstep at a time; 5\u2014Be persistent.\nHold to your course; 6\u2014Be a worker.\nWork your brain more than your\nbody; 7\u2014Be a student. Know your\njob; 8\u2014Be fair. Treat the other\nman as you would be treated; 9\u2014\nBe temperate. Avoid excess in any\nthing; 10\u2014Be confident. Have the\nfaith that cannot be weakened.\"\nBROWN U. PROF.\nWINS PRIX MOULIN\nProvidence, R. I., March 21\u2014(UP)\n\u2014Professor Harcourt Brown, chair\nman of the department of romance\nlanguages and literatures at Brown\nUniversity, has been granted the\nPrix Moulin, honorary award for\ndistinctive scholarly research, by the\nAcademie Des Sciences, Arts Et\nBelles Lettres at Caen, Prance, it\nwas announced today.\nThe award, including a stipend of\n2000 francs, and a membership in\nthe academy, was for Brown's paper\non the life and times of Andre\nGraindorge, French physician and\nsecretary of the academy from 1666\nuntil 1672.\nPOLICE CONTINUE\nGANG ROUND-UP\nNew Britain, Conn., March 21\n(UP)\u2014Local and state police con\ntinued a round-up today of mem\nbers of an alleged gang of store\nthieves In Massachusetts and Con\nnecticut after arresting eight men\nover the weekend.\nThe arrests increased to 20 the\nnumber of persona now held on\ncharges of receiving stolen goods,\nburglary and arson.\nThe gang was said to have used\nthis city as a base.\nHitler \u201cAsks\u201d Four More Years\nStrikingly reminiscent of the last German election, in which Adolf\nHitler polled 98 per cent of the vote on a ballot marked only \"yes,\u201d was\nthe dramatic scene shown In the above radiophoto when Der Fuehrer,\nindicated by arrow, appeared before the Reichstag In Berlin asking\n\u201canother four years that I may complete the tasks ahead in the German\nReich.\u201d Defending his coup in Austria, hurling an implied warning at\nCzechoslovakia, Hitler announced dissolution of the Reichstag and called\nfor legislative elections for the new Pan Germany on April 10, the same\ndate on which Austrians will vote to \u201cdecide\u201d whether they want to be\nannexed by Germany.\nGreatest Fleet In U.S.\nHistory In Prospect\n(Continued from Page 1)\ncarry out the terms of a possible\ntreaty, but forbids suspension or\nscrapping of ships actually under\nconstruction, as done by the United\nStates under the Washington treaty.\nOriginally this section carried a\nstatement of policy committing the\nUnited States to a fleet powerful\nenough to defend both coasts simul\ntaneously and to protect our terri\ntories and possessions as well as\n\u201ccommerce and citizens abroad.\u2019\u2019\nOpponents of the measure, fearing\nthis indicated the enlarged fleet was\nto be used for aggression abroad,\nconcentrated attack on this provi\nsion. It was eliminated on a point\nCROSS MAY NOT\nBE OPPOSED\n(Continued from Page 1)\ntions showed conclusively the Re\npublican vote elected the governor.\nThere was some sentiment for\nrunning Socialist Mayor Jasper Mc\nLevy, Bridgeport, providing he was\nwilling to accept the gubernatorial\nnomination. The contingent favor\ning this move declared the various\ninvestigations of the past few\nmonths would draw support from\nmany sources for McLevy.\nAmong others prominently men\ntioned to head the ticket were for\nmer secretary of state John A.\nDanaher, Hartford; Former Lieut.\nGov. Roy Wilcox, Meriden; State's\nAttorney Hugh M. Alcorn, both for\ngovernor and U. S. senator; Arthur\nM. Brown, Jewett City, also in con\nnection with both nominations; Al\nbert E. Lavery, Fairfield; Rep. Noah\nSwayne, Darien, and President\nJames L. McConaughy, Wesleyan\nuniversity.\nThe present concensus was that\nthe party would nominate its own\ngubernatorial candidate without\ncalling on McLevy. Many leaders\nwere Impatient to lay the ground\nwork early for the fall campaign.\nReports were that state central com\nmittee Chairman Benjamin E. Har\nwood, Chester, had accepted that\npost only to carry on until just\nbefore the campaign. There was no\nopposition to Harwood among the\nrank and file but the feeling was\ngeneral that if a change were to be\nmade, a decision should be arrived\nat early, and within the next two\nor three months at the least.\nLEWIS NOT AFTER\nPOLITICAL OFFICE\nBoston, March 21 (UP) John\nL. Lewis Is not a candidate for\npresident, according to Homer W.\nMartin, president of the United\nAutomobile Workers.\n\u201cHe has told me so,\u201d Martin said\nIn an Interview. \"I know Mr. Lewis\npretty well and It is my opinion that\nhe wouldn\u2019t take the presidency.\u201d\nMartin denied that he, Lewis,\nDavid Dubinsky, Sidney Hillman\nand other leaders of the committee\nfor Industrial organization favored\nCommunism. All are opposed to the\ntheories of totalitarian and authori\ntarian systems of government, he\nsaid.\nJEWISH WRITER IN\nVIENNA IS SUICIDE\nVienna, March 21\u2014(UP)\u2014Egon\nPriedell, 60-year-old Jewish writer,\nplaywright and actor, committed\nsuicide today.\nPriedell, whose \u201chistory of world\ncultui*e\u201c was published in England\nand the United States, took his life\nby jumping from a fourth floor win\ndow.\nArrival at Linz today of Dr.\nHJalmar Schacht, president of the\nGerman Reichsbank, was believed to\nbe the forerunner of economic con\nferences on the union of Austria\nand Germany.\nThe United States Army has re\ncently completed an automobile\nlanding device which operates on\nthe radio compass. The controls\nare not touched by human hands\nor feet during the takeoff or the\nlanding.\nof order.\nThe two groat points of house\ncontroversy\u2014naval policy and the\nwisdom of continuing to build bat\ntleships\u2014are certain to be revived in\nthe senate. Opponents of the bill\u2019s\nauthorization of three battleships\nmaintained that a dreadnaught is\nprimarily an offensive weapon and\nthat the development of air attack\nhas made huge battleships obsolete.\nMust Match Others\nHouse members, however, agreed\nwith the contention of high rank\ning naval officers that as long as\nother nations continue to build\nbatlesliips the United States must\nmatch them.\nThe United States is the only na\ntion in the world which imposes on\nitself a limit of naval construction.\nThe legislation was necessary be\ncause present law permits only\nenough tonnage to reach the limits\nof the London naval treaty of 1930,\nno longer observed by Japan. Build\ning beyond those limits by Great\nBritain and Japan required further\nauthorization in the United States\nif this nation was to match them\nand maintain the 5\u20145\u20143 ratio.\nAppropriation bills will be required\nbefore any of the ships can actually\nbe started.\nFOREIGN OIL COS.\nTO TAKE ACTION\n(Continued from Page 1)\nthe ground that the companies were\n\u201cin rebellion\u2019\u2019 against court orders\nto raise wages\u2014was unconstitu\ntional.\nFor the present the oil industry\nwas paralyzed, American business\nwas nearly paralyzed and oil com\npany workers were in control of all\ncompany offices throughout the re\npublic.\nDispatches from oil centers re\nported a mass flight of American\nand British oil company employes\nwith their families. Some took\ntrains, others airplaies; some gave\ntheir furniture to their servants be\nfore starting, despairing of ever re\nturning to their jobs.\nGenerally, the oil country was\nZOU\u2014W UKL\u2014Hartford\u20141330\nP. M.\n4:00\u2014Chapel Choir of Capitol Uni\nversity.\n4:15\u2014Columbia Concert Hall.\n4:150\u2014Tnose Happy Gilmans.\n4:45\u2014Yodlin* Jim Ingalls.\n5:00\u2014Ad Liner\u2014Danco Program.\n5:i:0\u2014Stepmother.\n5:45\u2014Hilltop House\u2014starring Bess\nJohnson.\n6:00\u2014News Service\u2014United Press\nNewscast.\n6:15\u2014WDFtC String Ensemble\u2014\nJoseph Blumo, director.\n6:150\u2014Boake Carter.\n6:45\u2014Lu mand Abner.\n7:00\u2014Poetic Melodics\u2014Jack Ful\nton, tenor; Franklyn Mac\nCormack.\n7:15\u2014Arthur Godfrey.\n7:30\u2014Among Our Souvenirs.\nfl:00\u2014Monday Night Show.\n8:30\u2014Pick and Pat in the Pipe\nSmoking Time.\n0:00\u2014Lux Radio Theater.\n10:00\u2014Wayne King\u2019s Orch.\n10:30\u2014Bravo New World\u2014U. S.\nOffice of Education.\n11:00\u2014Sports\u2014News\u2014late resume\nof United Press News.\n11:15\u2014Jimmy Dorsey\u2019s Orch.\n11:30\u2014East vs. West Golden Gloves\nNew England Amateur Box\ning Championships from\nBoston Gardens.\n12:00\u2014Jack Crawford\u2019s Orch.\nA. M.\n12:30\u2014Orrln Tucker\u2019s Orch.\n1530--WBRY\u201496\nP. M.\n3:00\u2014Connecticut Colonials.\n3:30\u2014Mary Roberts, soprano.\n3:45\u2014Good Health and Training.\n4:00\u2014The Rhode Islanders.\n4:30\u2014Better Homes Program.\n5:00\u2014Adventures of Speed Gibson.\n5:15\u2014Dine and Dance.\n5:30\u2014Curley\u2014The Yodelling Vow\nboy.\n5:45\u2014News.\n6:00\u2014Waterbury Catholic Hour.\n6:30\u2014News.\n6:45\u2014John G. Gllmartln, words.\n7:00\u2014Correct Time.\n7:00\u2014Sports of the Day.\n7:05\u2014News.\n7:10\u2014Band Music.\n7:15\u2014News of New Haven with\nDick Walsh.\n7:30\u2014Musical Workshop.\n7:45\u2014Words and Music with Mary\nBurke.\n8:00\u2014New Haven Catholic Hour.\n8:30\u2014Spelling Master.\n9:00\u2014New Haven Symphony and\nCivic Orch.\n10:00\u2014Cocoanut Grove Orch.\n10:30\u2014Henry Weber's Pageant of\nMelody.\n11:00\u2014Correct Time\u2014News.\n11:15\u2014Billy Brookes and His Hotel\nTaft Orch.\n11:30\u2014East va. West Golden Glove*\nBoxing Bouts*\nMOTORIST TO\nBE SENTENCED\n(Continued from Page 1)\nfor the accident. Patrolman Walter\nAhearn said that at police head\nquarters Meade made a disturbance\nand threatened to have several offi\ncers fired.\nFrank DeSimone, 23, of 152\nCharles street, pleaded guilty to\ncharges of evading responsibility\nand driving while his license was\nunder suspension. Sentence was de\nferred until tomorrow. DeSimone\nwas arrested at his home Saturday\nnight after having fled the scene\nwhen his car struck a parked auto\nmobile on Bank street. He first\nclaimed another man was driving\nhis car but later admitted that he\nwas the operator. DeSimone was\narrested on an evading responsibil\nity charge also in December.\nGiven Nolles\nThe following drivers received\nnolles on payment of the sums\nnoted: Herbert Liebrieck, 48, of\nGreen street, New Britain, rules of\nthe road, $5; Emil Gouery; 38, of\nWhite Plains, N. Y., rules of the\nroad, $5; Robert K. Warland, Jr.,\n20, of Thomaston, failure to grant\nthe right of way, $5; Samuel Gold\nfarb, 24, of 198 Chapel street, Hart\nford, rules of the road, $10; William\nAlbon, 51, of Cornwall avenue, rules\nof the road, $5.\nThe following drivers received\nnolles without payment: Manzer\nFinnemore, 31, of 35 Grandview\navenue, failure to grant the right\nof way; Morris Kaplan, 72, of 72\nNewell Place, failure to grant the\nright of way; Thomas Clapp, 63, of\n250 Cherry street, failure to grant\nthe right of way; Joseph Rocco, 26,\nof 821 North Main street, failure to\ngrant the right of way.\nquiet and orderly, it was reported\u2014\nwith the workers having seized\ncontrol of plants. One newspaper\nreported that laborers \u201cin a burst of\nenthusiasm\" caused damage to some\nplants in southern Vera Cruz state.\ni\nGRIEVE, BISSET HOLLAND, INC.\n\"Waterbury's Dependable Store\"\nHOME DECORATIONS\nI\nCurtains, Draperies, Tapestries, Pillows,\nCurtaining by the Yard, Venetian Blinds,\nWindow Shades\nAnd scores more of useful furnishings that mean beauty\nand charm for your home, are here for your approval.\nOur usual good service in helping you with your decora\ntive problems is at your command!\nChintz Draperies\nDistinctive patterns in a complete assortment of colors. Plaited tops\nand ruffled edges. 2 1/3 yards long.\nPriced at $1.98 pair\nCottage Sets\nAttractive figured voile and dotted organdie. Bright, colorful and\nsmart. Carefully tailored. Standard size.\nPriced from $1.19 to $2.98 set\nVenetian Blinds\nMade to order to fit your individual windows. Equipped with the\nnewest mechanism. Rustproof hardware. Variety of colors. No charge\nfor estimates or installation.\nPriced at 45c per square foot\nJUST RECEIVED\u2014\nA SPRING LINE OF QUAKER LACE CURTAINS\nChenille Rugs\nHeavy textured. Fast to sun and\nlaundering. Smart pattern. Col\nors include rose, gold, blue,\ngreen, black and burgundy.\nSize 24x36 Inches\nPriced at $1.69 each\nSize 27x54 Inches\nPriced at $2.69 each\nWindow Shades\nWe are equipped to care for all\ntypes of window shade work\nfrom small replacement jobs to\ncomplete home installation. Es\ntimates gladly furnished. We\ncarry complete color lines of\nseveral grades of Holland and\nPyrox finish shades. 36x72\ninches.\nPriced from 69c to $1.49 ea.\n\u201cBissell\u201d Carpet Sweepers\nSeveral popular models to choose\nfrom. All guaranteed and made\nIn the well-known \u201cBissell\u201d way.\nEquipped with the latest im\nprovements including self-ad\njusting brush, rubber bumpers,\nand cyco-bearings.\nPriced from $5.50 to\n$6.75 each\nROAMING THE AIR WAVES\nMary Pickford, Walter Lippman,\nand General Hugh S. Johnson will\nbe heard through the facilities of\nWMCA at a broadcast of the 1938\nCitizens\u2019 Appeal dinner of the Sal\nvation Army to be held at the Hotel\nPierre on Tuesday. The broadcast\nwill be heard from 9:30 to 9:45 p.\nm. The dinner will initiate the or\nganization\u2019s fund raising campaign\nfor $600,000 with which to continue\nthe work of the Army, and one of\nthe highlights of the event will be\na review of several hundred uni\nformed officers, cadets and nurses.\nThe \u201cYankee News Reporter\u201d,\nmirroring New England headline\nevents for New England listeners,\nin a series of tri-weekly quarter\nhoar broadcasts, will start on the\nYankee Network on Tuesday,\nMarch 22, at 7:30 p. m., EST. The\nprogram will be heard on Tues\ndays, Thursday and Saturdays at\nthat time. A program of time\nly Interest to all New Englanders\nthe \u201cYankee News Reporter\u201d will\ncombine vividly recreated drama\ntizations of headline events with\nmicrophone interviews with peo\nple who actually figured in the\nnews. Sports, politics, society\u2014all\nhappenings of headline interest in\nNew England will be covered.\nMrs. Ida Gorington, a lady ice\nman who delivers to such celebrities\nas Gene Tunney and Heywood\nBroun on her route in Stamford,\nConn., will be interviewed as the\n\"Person You Didn\u2019t Expect to\nMeet\u2019\u2019 by Fred Allen on Wednesday,\nMarch 27 at 9:00 p. m., EST, over\nthe'NBC-Red Network. Also\nhighlighting the full hour of fun\nand frolic will be Portland Hoffa,\nHarry von Zell, the Mighty Allen\nArt Players, Peter van Steeden and\nhis Troubadours, the Town Hall\nQuartet under the direction of Ken\nChristie, and the Merry Macs, vocal\nswing quartet featuring pretty Helen\nCarroll.\nGeorge Arliss, who just a few\nweeks ago did his first play on the\nair, returns again for another en\ngagement today. This time his\nvehicle will be \u201cThe Man Who\nPlayed God,\u201d one of his most suc\ncessful picture roles. With Cecil\nB. DeMille directing, it will be\nbroadcast over the Columbia net\nwork at 9:00 p. m. (EST).\n\u201cSpring Comes to the Arctic\u201d, will\nbe the theme of a special shortwave\nbroadcast to America from the Mac\nGregor Arctic Expedition at Rein\n500- W ICC-Brldgeport-600\nP. M.\n4:00\u2014The Rhode Islanlers Orch.\n4:30\u2014Club Matinee\u2014featuring\nWalter Blaufuss Orch. and\nsoloists: Ransom Sherman,\nmaster of ceremonies.\n5:00\u2014Street Scene from New Ha\nven, sidewalk interview.\n5:16\u2014Hon Winslow of the Navy,\ndramatic sketch.\n5:30\u2014WICC news bulletins and\nMusical Roundup.\n5:45\u2014Tom Mix and his Straight\nShooters.\ng:00\u2014Yankee Network News Serv\nice.\n6:15\u2014Money Matters.\n6:30\u2014Musical Rendezvous.\n6:45\u2014Bellmen Male Chorus.\n7:00\u2014WICC Spelling Bee with Bill\nElliott.\n7:30\u2014The Lone Ranger, dramatic\nsketch of the Old West.\n8:00\u2014Melody Puzzles featuring\nSalter's Orch., with Buddy\nClark and Freddie Gibson,\nsoloists and dramatic cast.\n8:30\u2014\"Grand Hotel,\" dramatic\nsketch starring Jim Ameche\nand Betty Lou Gerson.\n9:00\u2014New Haven Symphony Orch.\nConcert. Richard Donovan,\nconductor, with Julia Effon,\npianist.\n10:00\u2014\"Behind Prison Bars.\u201d with\nWarden Lewis E. Lawes,\ndra ma.\n10:30\u2014News from Yale University.\n10:35\u2014Henry Weber's Pageant of\nMelody\u2014featuring Henry\nWeber\u2019s Orch. ad Attlllo\nBagglore. tenor.\n11:00\u2014Yankee Network News Serv\nice.\n11:15\u2014Yankee Network Weather\nService.\n11:30\u2014Local News Bulletins.\n11:35\u2014East and West Finals\u2014\nGolden Gloves Boxing Bouts\nfrom Madison Square Garden\ndescribed by Dave Driscoll.\n12:00\u2014Red Norvo and his Orch.\n12:30\u2014\"Kyser College of Musical\nKnowledge.\u2019\u2019\n1:30\u2014Ray Keating and his Orch.\nVIRGINIA MAYOR 93\nDanville, Va. (UP)\u2014Capt. Harry\nWooding, Confederate veteran who\nhas outlived nearly all the men\nmany younger than himself\u2014with\nwhom he fought in the Civil War,\nbelieves he is the oldest active\nmayor in the United States. He is\nmayor of Danville at age of 93.\nDeanna Wows Her Boss\nDeanna Durbin\u2019s high notes surprise Eddie Cantor in